SIMPLE: rudiment
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rudiment
<hw>Ru"di*ment</hw> <pr>(r⟦udd⟧"d⟦icr⟧*m⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>rudimentum</ets>, fr. <ets>rudis</ets> unwrought,
ignorant, rude: cf. F. <ets>rudiment</ets>. See <er>Rude</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is unformed or undeveloped; the principle
which lies at the bottom of any development; an unfinished
beginning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>but I will bring thee where thou soon shalt quit⟦br⟧
Those <qex>rudiments</qex>, and see before thine eyes⟦br⟧
The monarchies of the earth.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>the single leaf is the <qex>rudiment</qex> of beauty in
landscape.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, an element or first principle of any art or
science; a beginning of any knowledge; a first step.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This boy is forest-born,⟦br⟧
And hath been tutored in the <qex>rudiments</qex>⟦br⟧
of many desperate studies.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There he shall first lay down the <qex>rudiments</qex>⟦br⟧
Of his great warfare.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>An imperfect organ or part, or
one which is never developed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rudiment</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rudiment
<hw>Ru"di*ment</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To furnish with first
principles or rules; to insrtuct in the rudiments.</def>
<rj><au>Gayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rudimental</ent>⟦br⟧
